sought to eliminate the borderline and turn the region into the "Middle Shires" of a united Great Britain. This book shows that, though the official borderline disappeared after union, the unique administrative arrangements, social and economic bonds of kinship, and built landscape served to uphold the notion of continued separation between the kingdoms. It highlights the movement of peoples across the borderline, collaboration attempts between local officials, and the formation of temporary cross-border alliances but also the assertion of national differences through periodic lawlessness, conflict, and outright war. The book thus demonstrates the complexities of the common border zone and the significance of the border in shaping distinct national identities. JENNA M. SCHULTZ teaches in the Department of History at the University of St Thomas inSt Paul, Minnesota.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBorderlandsxSocial aspectszScottish Borders (England and Scotland). 0aNational characteristics, EnglishxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, ScottishxHistory. 0aNationalismxHistoryy16th centuryzScottish Borders (England and Scotland). 0aNationalismxHistoryy17th centuryzScottish Borders (England and Scotland). 0aNationalismzScottish Borders (England and Scotland)xHistoryy16th century. 0aNationalismzScottish Borders (England and Scotland)xHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Scottish Borderlands.  aConflict.  aCross-Border Interactions.  aEarly Modern.  aNational Differences.  aNational Identity.  aPolitical Circumstances.  aSeparation.  aUnion of the Crowns.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787445321?